pull_request.title: Vonn's refactoring
pull_request.body:
eeeeeek

But yeah go through everything, see if it still works.

Stuff I changed:
* All the `aiGame[type].py` files are merged into one
* The second half of development's AI structure, after we added a layer to the AI, is called `strategy=1`, while the old strategy is `strategy=0`. You'll see references to this in all the `tetroNet[type].py` files and the `ai.py`'s prompts.
* `ai.py` can now be run on its own to simulate games just like the old `aiGame[type].py` files.
* `ai.py` handles the training function, and also plays a game after each step, so I removed the game-playing code from all the `evaluation[type].py` files.
* `evaluation[type].py` files now have some space to breathe.
* The tryhard percentage is now flipped, for a clearer meaning. It used to be 0.9 = 90% = "A ninety percent chance of not tryharding", but now it's 0.1 = 10% = "A ten percent chance of tryharding"

If you have any questions/problems/errors, please tell me!

comment.body:
Oh gosh, also forgot some more stuff:

* The `gameWindow` class has been created. It controls game display, everyXFrames stuff, OS events, and the pygame window.
* I forgot to actually finish some of the new scoring functions in `game.py`, so you can safely ignore them.
* All backups are now saved to a backup folder, to reduce clutter.
* `game.py` got a fancy upgrade, and now it looks nice and has a Next display.

issue.title: Slim files down to only 3 core files again?
issue.body:
It's going to be hard maintaining several different copies of the `game.py` and `evaluation.py` files, and I think we could just slim this down to just the 3 core files again.

Also, it might be a good idea to put the save files in their own directory and gitignore the `__pycache__` directory.
